rs are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/17/03 8:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2919.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   WHOA!  Thank you warriors!</span><hr size=1> I've spent a considerable amount of time reading some of the various aggro management posts this morning.  I've gained a wealth of info and what I hope will be a great idea.  I'll run it past you folks to see what you think.<br>
<br>
Habitually, as a ranger in PoP, I'm the puller.  (Fun, sometimes dangerous and sometimes I get to make a fairly messy pile of ranger goo on the ground.)  Now, as I understand the taunt ability (and I really learned this only recently), a success just catapults you immediately to the top of the critter's food chain.  After understanding that, I read a post about piggybacking aggro.  This is what brought up my idea.  Typically, I'll snare on the pull, jolt it on the way back, drag the not-yet-dead near camp and if a warrior is the tank (and a smart one at that), he/she will move out to intercept and engage.  Now, since we already know from long experience of selling the pieces of their bodies back to dumb rangers and dumb druids (myself included while I was growing up) snare is one of the highest level aggro spells in the game.  That initial snare is putting me well up on the list.  Then I proceed to wipe 500 points of that hate away before the warrior engages.<br>
<br>
What if...<br>
What if I just keep the snare aggro and jolt AFTER the successful taunt?  That gives the warrior all of my &quot;hate points&quot; and I can then immediately drop myself 500 points below the warrior.  Plus (in theory), the warrior now has a much much better chance of maintaining aggro through the slow since my aggro was piggybacked.  Not knowing the precise numbers of the hate generated by snaring as compared to slowing, I cannot say for certain that the slower won't get whacked a couple times; but it seems to me that the warrior should now have less problems getting the critter off the slower.  So I want the opinions of warriors on that.  Feasible or not?  Hmmm...as an additional benefit, it will put me on any rampage list and I am typically out of melee range using my bow.<br>
<br>
On the aggro issue, I really believe that taunt effectiveness should be increased at least slightly for warriors <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>only</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Knights don't need the extra ability, and I don't want it at all as a ranger if it can be helped.  I can't stand the idea of them nerfing anyone, so a small warrior tune-up is my suggestion.  I'm not saying taunt needs to work 100% of the time.  That would just make the entire game trivial.  What I'd like to see is taunt work often enough for warriors that a knight actually <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>must</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> chain cast to keep aggro from a warrior.  Any knights that read this, don't get me wrong.  I'll take either a warrior or a knight as a tank.  I just have to play a bit differently depending on who the tank is.  I'm perfectly willing to do that. <p>Kelliani Aspenwall<br>
